mxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBj=
YXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEM=
iLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.WqT_RidQwUaCQ4WGbu44ViOFJpkqWCr_pEnSKIywpsuzpgkL04B=
NyoT3zIujex7djCjZr0r11mWMXNCZ01moz0vshT-DodcdHPalpXYMeladsPuAUg4RjP6rVoatBn=
l0QLKbHV0xWLp5zJFAm1LLJZB0ds3RH-xheQnT2kt1BK1LfbHUZZRvwfO2e1J9s0pYeH3I3wIYU=
lhSGUdUBSe3ZgAn52FErra_E4cMg4Ym9m8yF9B58J1rGE2JFSr7oaoh83X1y1ZeOfEJy_OVJEMl=
Ubux6fREpRRPNhI5anpQVYW-KSvTjAe00yX_skXUizwwQQt3YXtqTD17OcYF-XRdEA ) was to=
 take a very high level view of various companies=E2=80=99 approaches to AI=
; take Google, for example: yes, the company offers a variety of models on =
its Vertex AI platform, as well as Nvidia GPUs, but (1) Google itself is us=
ing its own models on its own TPUs and (2) to the extent the company can tr=
uly drive meaningful shifts in cloud marketshare I strongly suspect that it=
s integration will be a central factor. In other words, I was trying to get=
 at the core drivers of a company=E2=80=99s strategy, not make an itemized =
list of their overall offerings; see also Microsoft, and pointing out the f=
act that its modularization arguments ring somewhat hollow in the light of =
the company=E2=80=99s professed differentiation just last fall, which was p=
redicated on integration with OpenAI=E2=80=99s models.

It was in that context that I mentioned AWS mostly in passing, labeling the=
m as a fully modular player:

On the other extreme is AWS, which doesn=E2=80=99t have any of its own mode=
ls; instead its focus has been on its Bedrock managed development platform,=
 which lets you use any model. Amazon=E2=80=99s other focus has been on dev=
eloping its own chips, although the vast majority of its AI business runs o=
n Nvidia GPUs.

This is incorrect (and I have corrected the original Article, and apologize=
 for the error): AWS released its Titan family of foundation models ( https=
://aws.amazon.com/bedrock/titan/ ) the same time it announced Bedrock; ther=
e are several text generation models, text embedding models, a multimodal e=
mbedding model, and an image generator. AWS has also been touting their Tra=
inium and Inferentia training and inference chips; you can of course run Ti=
tan models on Inferentia chips on Bedrock. However, Titan was actually trai=
ned on Nvidia chips ( https://blogs.nvidia.com/blog/nemo-amazon-titan/ ) , =
and used Nvidia=E2=80=99s own orchestration layer, not AWS Sagemaker.

To that end, I=E2=80=99m not prepared to fully back down from my contention=
 that AWS is a modular player in AI. Yes, they are making moves at every le=
vel of the stack, and indeed there very well may be more loads on Inferenti=
a than Nvidia (although I question how many of those loads are specifically=
 LLMs). However, my perception is not that AWS is creating an integrated of=
fering that has superior performance because every part of the stack was de=
signed to work together, but rather is offering a collection of models (som=
e of them their own) on a variety of chips (some of them their own), mostly=
 with the goal of servicing existing AWS customers that want to easily leve=
rage their data that already exists on AWS. As I wrote later on in the Arti=
cle:

Amazon is certainly hoping that argument is correct: the company is operati=
ng as if everything in the AI value chain is modular and ultimately a commo=
dity, which implies that it believes that data gravity will matter most. Wh=
at is difficult to separate is to what extent this is the correct interpret=
ation of the strategic landscape versus a convenient interpretation of the =
facts that happens to perfectly align with Amazon=E2=80=99s strengths and w=
eaknesses, including infrastructure that is heavily optimized for commodity=
 workloads.

To me that last line is the most pressing question I have about AWS: the co=
mpany=E2=80=99s real integration is Nitro, the customized virtualization in=
frastructure that undergirds its EC2 platform. Dylan Patel at SemiAnalysis =
( https://www.semianalysis.com/p/amazons-cloud-crisis-how-aws-will ) descri=
bed Nitro thusly:

All the way back in ~2012, an engineer at AWS, had an idea. Why not place a=
 =E2=80=98dongle=E2=80=99, a dedicated piece of hardware, between every EC2=
 instance and the outside world so that all data would flow through it? Thi=
s dongle would run security, networking, and virtualization tasks such as t=
he hypervisor. The benefits of the =E2=80=98dongle=E2=80=99 would have the =
immediate benefit of improving performance, cost, and security for EC2 inst=
ances while also enabling bare metal instances. What started as a little id=
ea was able to turn into the entire custom silicon effort of Amazon, which =
designs many different chips and saves them tens of billions of dollars a y=
ear.

AWS set out a specification for a custom chip that would support this dongl=
e idea. The requirements were simple, a dual-core Arm-based System-on-Chip =
(SoC), that could be PCIe attached. After approaching several firms, AWS wo=
rked with Cavium on the challenge of building a custom SoC at a cost that w=
ouldn=E2=80=99t lead to a material increase in the cost of each EC2 server.=
 The resulting Cavium part was delivered soon after. The whole system, with=
 the custom SoC on a discrete PCIe card and associated software, was named =
=E2=80=98Nitro System=E2=80=99. It first appeared (although it wasn=E2=80=
=99t initially discussed publicly) in C3, R2, and I2, EC2 instances. By Aug=
ust 2022, AWS had over 20 million Nitro parts installed over four generatio=
ns, with every new EC2 server installing at least one Nitro part.

The primary cost benefit of this =E2=80=9Cdongle=E2=80=9D is that it offloa=
ds Amazon=E2=80=99s management software, the hypervisor, which would otherw=
ise run on an existing CPU. The most commonly deployed CPU across Amazon=E2=
=80=99s infrastructure was, and still is, an Intel 14nm 24-core CPU. Even t=
o this day, other clouds, such as Microsoft Azure eat as many as 4 CPU core=
s on workloads that aren=E2=80=99t the customers=E2=80=99. If this held tru=
e across all of Amazon=E2=80=99s infrastructure, that would be as much as a=
 ~15% reduction in the number of VMs for existing servers and, therefore, r=
evenue. Even with much more conservative estimates of 2 CPU cores saved per=
 Nitro, with per-core cost estimated at 1/4th that of reserved list price, =
the savings of Nitro exceed $7 billion annually.

There=E2=80=99s just one problem, as Patel points out later in that Article=
:

Amazon is actively hampering its efforts in AI clusters. Compute is only pa=
rt of the equation. Networking is the other side and arguably just as impor=
tant. Rather than implement the best networking from Nvidia and/or Broadcom=
, Amazon is using its own Nitro and Elastic Fabric Adaptor (EFA) networking=
. This works well for many workloads, plus it delivers a cost, performance,=
 and security advantage. There are business, cultural, and security reasons=
 why Amazon will not implement other networking. The cultural one is import=
ant. Nitro and networking SoC=E2=80=99s generally have been Amazon=E2=80=99=
s biggest cost advantage for years. It=E2=80=99s ingrained into their DNA. =
Even EFA delivers on this too, but they don=E2=80=99t see how new workloads=
 are evolving and that a new tier is needed due to the lack of foresight in=
 their internal workload and infrastructure teams. Amazon is making a delib=
erate choice of not adopting that we believe will bite them in the future.

