One of the reasons I think AWS did not invest in some of these lower latenc=
y solutions early on was just the pure cost, these are at least 10x more ex=
pensive data centers to build. From an investing dollars perspective, from =
a cloud provider, is it worth spending a dollar on commodity where =E2=80=
=94 computing where it=E2=80=99s less volatile, I know what I=E2=80=99m goi=
ng to get. I know my business ROI there versus something like specialized c=
omputing where the appreciation curves are faster, the workloads are much m=
ore volatile. It=E2=80=99s an industry that=E2=80=99s still early days to c=
loud.

In short, I do think AWS is integrated in commodity cloud computing; unfort=
unately I think there is a good chance that that integration is actually a =
hindrance in building out a truly competitive AI cloud for the most demandi=
ng workloads. That=E2=80=99s the thing, though, and why their modular strat=
egy may not even be wrong: it=E2=80=99s not yet clear that a fully integrat=
ed approach matters more than having the data and customers in the first pl=
ace, with good enough AI offerings that let the customer pick-and-choose th=
e components. Figuring that out will fall to new AWS CEO Matt Garman ( http=
s://www.aboutamazon.com/news/company-news/leadership-update-aws-adam-selips=
ky-matt-garman ).

